comments.content:
@paragraph: you assumed correctly; my question was pertaining to pairing Univers and Sabon. I did digress, as I was quite inspired by people's responses! Any more thoughts? I'd love to hear more about using TNR, and do you mean using it with Univers? An interesting thought. I suppose one could argue that Times is ubiquitous and thought of as generic. Univers and Helvetica too are ubiquitous and generic in their versatility. I did use Times recenly in a piece that called for recreating a NYTimes headline. New possible topic for anyone who would like to respond: when was the last time you used Times?

Thanks,

Cory

Thanks for the comments everyone!

@altaira: The whole point of modernism is to go beyond a time or context. It is not about nostalgia for any one period or time. Rand & Vignelli are just good examples. It doesn't matter when they were around, it matters what they did!

As soon as you design within a time's context, whether you are going with it or against it, you are hurting your chances at creating timeless work.

Yes, the context has shifted, but it will always continue to do so. Do you want to be stuck in yesterday's context, or create something beyond context which will last?

Compare the 17,000 year old paintings in Lascaux (beyond context) to "post-modern" graphic design of the 1980's and 1990's. Which looks more dated?

@paragraph: I appreciate your concern, but I would think it is more important to save the real experimentation, learning & growth for actual work in my portfolio, not my business cards, which was the subject of the original post. What do you think?
